      "id": "RQ-0043",
      "status": "done",
      "title": "Redact secret-bearing webhook payload fields before persisting failures",
      "description": "Principles violated: I (security baseline), J (consistency/integrity), H (operational hygiene). Persisted webhook failure records sanitize `destination` and `error` but still clone `msg.payload` verbatim, so operator-supplied notes and other payload text leak into `.ralph/cache/webhooks/failures.json`. Why it matters: rejected-task notes and other webhook payload text can contain tokens, customer data, or raw error material, and the failure store keeps that content on disk for replay and local inspection. Minimal fix: sanitize or omit secret-bearing payload fields before writing `WebhookFailureRecord`, while keeping enough safe metadata for diagnostics and replay selection. Acceptance criteria: a failing-webhook regression proves persisted failure records no longer contain raw secret-bearing `payload.note` or equivalent unsanitized payload text, replay remains functional with the retained safe payload shape, and `cargo test -p ralph-agent-loop webhook` passes.",
